1
00:00:32,655 --> 00:00:35,274
Schafer: I need to get accustomed
to money being around.

2
00:00:35,274 --> 00:00:37,002
That's the thing.

3
00:00:37,002 --> 00:00:38,851
This is for the therapy,
the physical therapy

4
00:00:38,851 --> 00:00:41,029
of getting me used to actually
not being afraid of money.

5
00:00:41,029 --> 00:00:43,249
Offscreen voice: Richard Branson
does the same thing.

6
00:00:43,249 --> 00:00:46,755
Schafer: Ah! You guys, what is
this stuff that's all over me?

7
00:00:46,755 --> 00:00:48,287
Offscreen voice: Beautiful.

8
00:00:48,287 --> 00:00:49,552
Schafer: I can't apply it to myself..

9
00:00:49,552 --> 00:00:50,632
Offscreen voice: Oh my God.

10
00:00:50,632 --> 00:00:52,113
Schafer: I can't self-terminate.

11
00:00:52,113 --> 00:00:53,470
Offscreen voice: Help me apply money.

12
00:00:53,470 --> 00:00:55,872
Schafer: I can't self-monetize.

13
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:27,120
Schafer: So this is a more recent,
uh point-and-click adventure game.

14
00:01:27,186 --> 00:01:28,697
I have to show you someone else's,

15
00:01:28,697 --> 00:01:29,962
because I haven't made
one in a long time.

16
00:01:29,962 --> 00:01:31,565
I used to make them back in the '90s.

17
00:01:31,565 --> 00:01:33,569
This is Machinarium.

18
00:01:33,569 --> 00:01:35,512
You role play this little
robot and you click around.

19
00:01:35,512 --> 00:01:37,546
And these kind of games,
you walk the character around

20
00:01:37,546 --> 00:01:41,245
by clicking on the ground somewhere
and pull on this handle here.

21
00:01:41,245 --> 00:01:43,987
And then I can make this mine
cart come through the room.

22
00:01:43,987 --> 00:01:45,529
Shahani: I'm sorry. What's that?

23
00:01:45,529 --> 00:01:47,657
Schafer: I pulled this handle,
oh, that's right.

24
00:01:47,657 --> 00:01:49,968
This doesn't work until I do this.

25
00:01:49,968 --> 00:01:52,188
That's what a lot of adventure
game playing is like.

26
00:01:52,188 --> 00:01:54,622
You're like, oh, this doesn't,
why doesn't this work?

27
00:01:54,622 --> 00:01:56,166
Oh, I need this gear first.

28
00:01:56,166 --> 00:01:57,984
I need to get the gear on the sprocket.

29
00:01:57,984 --> 00:01:59,710
And so they're, they
move at a slower pace.

30
00:01:59,710 --> 00:02:01,775
And some people really like that.

31
00:02:01,775 --> 00:02:05,782
But it also means they're not
exactly as attention-getting

32
00:02:05,782 --> 00:02:10,126
and as visceral and maybe as a
big block buster action game.

33
00:02:10,126 --> 00:02:12,745
And it led us to this point
now where it's really hard

34
00:02:12,745 --> 00:02:14,565
to get one of these games
made these days,

35
00:02:14,565 --> 00:02:17,308
or at least get funding
for it from a publisher.

36
00:02:17,308 --> 00:02:20,513
Shahani: Before getting into all that,
what put you on the map?

37
00:02:20,513 --> 00:02:24,919
Like, just describe the game
that got you into game famous.

38
00:02:24,919 --> 00:02:26,615
Schafer: Game famous.

39
00:02:26,615 --> 00:02:29,142
You know, we just, each
game we made in the '90s,

40
00:02:29,142 --> 00:02:30,807
we got a little more recognition for it.

41
00:02:30,807 --> 00:02:33,417
And we were always pretty savvy
about getting our names on the box,

42
00:02:33,417 --> 00:02:34,995
you know, so we're, hey.

43
00:02:34,995 --> 00:02:39,305
You know, you have to kind of act
like you're famous before you're famous.

44
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:42,520
That sounds funny.

45
00:02:42,660 --> 00:02:45,280
I learned that from an interview with
David Lee Roth about Van Halen.

46
00:02:45,287 --> 00:02:47,230
Like we always acted
like we were hot shit.

47
00:02:47,230 --> 00:02:49,357
We had a big hit, Full Throttle,

48
00:02:49,357 --> 00:02:51,145
it's called Full Throttle and
it sold a million copies

49
00:02:51,145 --> 00:02:54,257
and that was really big for
those PC graphic adventures.

50
00:02:54,257 --> 00:02:56,385
And then I made a game
called Grim Fandango

51
00:02:56,385 --> 00:02:58,941
and that won Game of
the Year with Game Spot

52
00:02:58,941 --> 00:03:01,347
and that was the big
thing that helped a lot.

53
00:03:01,347 --> 00:03:05,978
Grim Fandango is set in the
Land of the Dead, yeah.

54
00:03:05,978 --> 00:03:09,215
And it was, it sold
about half a million units

55
00:03:09,215 --> 00:03:12,050
and it was seen as not
being commercially successful.

56
00:03:12,050 --> 00:03:14,792
And it was one of the reasons
 that adventure games died.

57
00:03:14,792 --> 00:03:17,413
I mean, I heard a friend of mine,
who worked in another game company,

58
00:03:17,413 --> 00:03:19,468
saying we tried to get
an adventure game made

59
00:03:19,468 --> 00:03:23,350
and they said, well look, you know,
Grim Fandango didn't do that well.

60
00:03:23,350 --> 00:03:26,493
So obviously, you know, it was
a good game, it won Game of the Year.

61
00:03:26,493 --> 00:03:28,313
And if Game of the Year can't sell,

62
00:03:28,313 --> 00:03:31,610
you know, as many copies as it
needs to, then maybe that genre's dead.

63
00:03:31,610 --> 00:03:37,750
So I feel some responsibility to make
a good game and make it do well.

64
00:03:39,020 --> 00:03:40,180
Rice: He's been excited about it.

65
00:03:40,180 --> 00:03:42,720
I mean, he's wanted to return to
adventure games for a while

66
00:03:42,725 --> 00:03:46,947
and it's just been a matter of not
knowing how to make that happen.

67
00:03:46,947 --> 00:03:50,398
Schafer: But fans are always saying
they would want, they want one,

68
00:03:50,398 --> 00:03:53,756
but a publisher would say, we
can't make money doing those.

69
00:03:53,756 --> 00:03:56,777
So something like Kickstarter shows up,

70
00:03:56,777 --> 00:04:00,773
which is this crowd sourcing website,
where everybody can back a project.

71
00:04:00,773 --> 00:04:04,367
You pitch your project and you get
backers and then if you meet your goals,

72
00:04:04,367 --> 00:04:06,310
you get the money and
you build your project.

73
00:04:06,310 --> 00:04:08,401
Doing an adventure game is interesting,

74
00:04:08,401 --> 00:04:10,468
because it's the only, like the
only way you could do that,

75
00:04:10,468 --> 00:04:14,319
letting the fans like, kind of put
their money where their mouth is.

76
00:04:14,319 --> 00:04:15,738
Is it that? Wait a second.

77
00:04:15,738 --> 00:04:17,219
Did I get that backwards? Yeah.

78
00:04:17,219 --> 00:04:18,267
Host: No, you're right. Yeah.

79
00:04:18,267 --> 00:04:19,994
Some loud mouth fan, no,
I don't want to buy Trenched,

80
00:04:19,995 --> 00:04:21,476
but what about an adventure game?

81
00:04:21,476 --> 00:04:23,541
Schafer: Exactly.

82
00:04:23,541 --> 00:04:24,837
Shahani: Explain your
Kickstarter campaign.

83
00:04:24,837 --> 00:04:26,596
What have you just done?

84
00:04:26,596 --> 00:04:29,676
Schafer: Yeah. What have we done?

85
00:04:29,676 --> 00:04:31,835
Schafer: Oh, sorry.
I didn't see you there.

86
00:04:31,835 --> 00:04:35,184
You caught me indulging in one
of my many impressive hobbies.

87
00:04:35,184 --> 00:04:36,727
I'm Tim Schafer.

88
00:04:36,727 --> 00:04:39,223
Schafer: And so we put a pitch video
up where we said we want to make a game.

89
00:04:39,223 --> 00:04:42,027
And the idea was, what if we made
one of these adventure games

90
00:04:42,027 --> 00:04:44,402
