118
00:05:49,724 --> 00:05:50,989
That's so great.

119
00:05:50,989 --> 00:05:53,085
We have too much money now.

120
00:05:53,085 --> 00:05:54,288
Damn you!

121
00:05:54,288 --> 00:05:56,755
Why haven't anyone given us any money?

122
00:05:56,755 --> 00:05:58,297
I'm so sad.

123
00:05:58,297 --> 00:06:00,733
That doesn't seem believable.

124
00:06:00,733 --> 00:06:02,265
Yeah, we're not going to use that one.

125
00:06:02,265 --> 00:06:03,684
Or just moderately, hello.

126
00:06:03,684 --> 00:06:07,013
Thank you for dedicating
the appropriate amount of...

127
00:06:07,013 --> 00:06:09,880
Schafer: Because the previous
projects in Kickstarter had only been,

128
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:11,514
I don't know what the
maximum was before then,

129
00:06:11,514 --> 00:06:13,796
but it looked like
they're like forty grand.

130
00:06:13,796 --> 00:06:17,494
You know, I mean, we're used to making
projects that were like, you know, BrÃ¼tal.

131
00:06:17,494 --> 00:06:19,990
Like 20 million dollars and these
smaller games, like two million.

132
00:06:19,990 --> 00:06:22,733
It was like, no way you can get
two million from Kickstarter.

133
00:06:22,733 --> 00:06:24,031
Could you?

134
00:06:24,031 --> 00:06:25,480
Schafer: I hope this works out,
because it is kind of,

135
00:06:25,480 --> 00:06:27,238
that enough people got together,

136
00:06:27,238 --> 00:06:29,334
are they going to actually make
a game like this happen?

137
00:06:29,334 --> 00:06:31,030
A game like, that we
haven't really been able to

138
00:06:31,030 --> 00:06:34,760
make happen for business reasons
for like, many, many years.

139
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:37,934
Gilbert: Or we'll just prove
all those publishers right.

140
00:06:37,934 --> 00:06:41,784
Schafer: Or we'll just
prove them all right.

141
00:07:03,980 --> 00:07:05,920
Schafer: No, I mean
nothing I had done before

142
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:08,247
prepared me for what it's
like to work with publishers.

143
00:07:08,247 --> 00:07:09,975
Rice: When you're
working with a publisher,

144
00:07:09,975 --> 00:07:14,259
a lot of times they get
involved with design decisions.

145
00:07:14,259 --> 00:07:16,816
And you have to make compromises.

146
00:07:16,816 --> 00:07:19,314
Gilbert: You know, if
a publisher is out there,

147
00:07:19,314 --> 00:07:23,229
from the outside kind of poking
in and making you do things.

148
00:07:23,229 --> 00:07:26,219
You know, that's where I think
things can kind of come off the rails.

149
00:07:26,219 --> 00:07:29,179
Schafer: And the way it felt,
I don't know if this makes any sense,

150
00:07:29,179 --> 00:07:31,398
but my head, like the creative process
of making a game was like,

151
00:07:31,398 --> 00:07:34,603
you look at a field of
floating, multi-colored dots,

152
00:07:34,603 --> 00:07:36,886
drifting slowly to the ground.

153
00:07:36,886 --> 00:07:38,613
And eventually when they hit the ground,

154
00:07:38,613 --> 00:07:40,587
they're going to make like
a painting on the floor.

155
00:07:40,587 --> 00:07:43,146
But you've got to kind of like move
them around, give them the right and see.

156
00:07:43,146 --> 00:07:45,273
And then as they fall, you start
to see where you need more color

157
00:07:45,273 --> 00:07:50,081
and you move them around and
slowly they settle and you just add a sound.

158
00:07:50,081 --> 00:07:51,376
And then you're done.

159
00:07:51,376 --> 00:07:54,212
So it'd be like, Tim, what do
you do with that green dot?

160
00:07:54,212 --> 00:07:55,632
Phew, I can't tell you.

161
00:07:55,632 --> 00:07:57,083
You're like, ok, that dot?

162
00:07:57,083 --> 00:07:58,131
Can we just nail that down here.

163
00:07:58,131 --> 00:07:59,151
Can we just say what that's going to be?

164
00:07:59,151 --> 00:08:00,200
And you're like, no.

165
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:01,558
So let's just say where all the
red dots are going to be, ok.

166
00:08:01,558 --> 00:08:02,823
Could you just nail
all the red dots down?

167
00:08:02,823 --> 00:08:03,996
Like, no!

168
00:08:03,996 --> 00:08:05,476
How about if we just start on this edge

169
00:08:05,476 --> 00:08:08,283
and we just take all the dots,
like this and just nail all those dots.

170
00:08:08,283 --> 00:08:09,546
No!

171
00:08:09,546 --> 00:08:11,491
Rice: Yeah. The games
industry as a whole, I think,

172
00:08:11,491 --> 00:08:15,374
is in a really weird
spot where it's like we're,

173
00:08:15,374 --> 00:08:19,257
like the film industry used
to be way back in the day.

174
00:08:19,257 --> 00:08:21,909
Where the publishers are
running mostly everything.

175
00:08:21,909 --> 00:08:23,913
That's kind of how it
was for a long time

176
00:08:23,913 --> 00:08:26,410
and it's only now that
people are starting to like

177
00:08:26,410 --> 00:08:29,175
seek out the creators of the games.

178
00:08:29,175 --> 00:08:30,903
That people who are making the game

179
00:08:30,903 --> 00:08:34,046
